            <abstract>
                <p>According to <bibl><ptr target="bm:Triulzi2006Orality"/><citedRange unit="page">50–51</citedRange></bibl>,
                    this text was collected and redacted by <persName ref="PRS4222Gabraeg"><roleName type="title">Daǧǧāč</roleName>
                    Gabra ʾƎgziʾabǝḥer alias Kumsaa Moroda</persName> <date notBefore="1920" notAfter="1923">in the early 1920ies</date>
                    based on information of elders in order to legitimise his position as leader of the Oromo in the region of 
                    <placeName ref="LOC4964Naqamt"/>. His draft version was banned from being printed by 
                    <persName ref="PRS5226haylase"/>. Later in <date when="1937">1937</date>, his son 
                    <persName ref="PRS4938HabtaMa">Hābta Māryām alias Hambissa Kumsaa</persName> updated the text by adding a short 
                    paragraph entitled <foreign xml:lang="am">Ya-Boranā ḥaggaru Horr Walābu naw</foreign> ‘The Boranā of the country 
                    Horr Walābu are ...’. This version, which is witnessed in <ref type="mss" corresp="ANLcr48"/>, came to the hands of 
                    <persName ref="PRS7170Moreno"/> and <persName ref="PRS3182ContiRo"/>, who produced two fragmentary 
                    translations in <ref type="mss" corresp="ANLcr48#accMat1"/> and <ref type="mss" corresp="ANLcr48#accMat2"/>.</p>
            </abstract>
